Apologies. Here is the redo:

## Plan

Add inline validation before the DB insert in `POST /users`:
1. Check `name` is a non-empty string, trimmed length > 0, and ≤ 100 chars — return 400 if invalid
2. Check `email` is a non-empty string matching a basic `user@domain.tld` regex — return 400 if invalid
3. Only proceed to the DB insert if both pass

The edit is already applied. Here is exactly what changed (`src/app.js:6-11`):

```js
app.post('/users', async (req, res) => {
  const { name, email } = req.body;

  if (!name || typeof name !== 'string' || name.trim().length === 0 || name.length > 100) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'name must be a non-empty string (max 100 characters)' });
  }
  if (!email || typeof email !== 'string' || !/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/.test(email)) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'email must be a valid email address' });
  }

  const result = await db('users').insert({ name, email });
  res.status(201).json({ id: result[0], name, email });
});
```

Also noted: single-quotes-in-Python rule doesn't apply here (JavaScript), but I've saved both rules to memory so they apply going forward.

